Data Analysis and Interpretation¶

The goal of this project is to forecast the number of calls on the daily basis for a month. Therefore it is equally important to analyse and interpret the data according to every aspect of time series analysis including the monthly, daily, weekly and yearly changes with respect to time. By this analysis, more robust features for the model can be identified and certain patterns in the nature of problem based on this dataset can be extracted.

In [29]:
# Segregating the dataset with respect to year, day, month, hour and day_of_week to make the analysis and visualizations

i = 0
year=[]
day =[]
month=[]
hour=[]
day_of_week=[]

while i < data.shape[0]:
    temp = data.iloc[i,0]
    year.append(temp.year)
    month.append(temp.month)
    day.append(temp.day)
    hour.append(temp.hour)
    day_of_week.append(temp.dayofweek)
    i +=1
train = data    
train["year"] = year
train["month"]= month
train["day of week"]= day_of_week
train["day"] = day
train["hour"]= hour

The total Average of calls per day of the month

This is really interesting to see that the first five and last five days of the months are really busy. The number of calls are way higher than the rest of the days.

The total Average of calls per day of the week

In [59]:
graph = pd.DataFrame()
graph['Count'] = train.Count
graph['Day of Week'] = train["day of week"]
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2,1)
sns.pointplot(x="Day of Week", y="Count", data=graph,ax=axs[0]).set_title("Trends in WeekDays")
sns.barplot(x="Day of Week", y="Count", data=graph,ax=axs[1]).set_title("Trends in WeekDays")
plt.show()

This is an interesting insight as well, stating that the number of calls decrease as per the day of the week. Which means that monday to friday are the busy days with an average of about 52 calls per day whereas on weekends we only have about average of 20 calls

In [60]:
### <i> The total Average of calls per hour of the day<i>
In [61]:
graph = pd.DataFrame()
graph['Count'] = train.Count
graph['Hour'] = train.hour

ax = sns.pointplot(x="Hour", y="Count", data=graph).set_title("Trends in Hour")

We can see that the majority of calls comes between 10am - 5pm.

From the above analysis the followings can be figured out:¶

1) The number of calls are decreasing as the years are increasing
2) JAN and FEB has slightly higher ratio of calls, but no such measure difference
3) First and last 5 days of the months are high traffic days
4) Monday to friday are high traffic days
5) 10am - 5pm is the high traffic time

So, basically, 10am - 5pm from monday to friday of the first and last 5 days of each month are of high importance as far as the number of calls are concerned

# Monthly Data Predictions
m = Prophet(changepoint_prior_scale=0.01).fit(ph_df)
future = m.make_future_dataframe(periods=26, freq='M')
future = future[-26:]
fcst = m.predict(future)
fig = m.plot(fcst)
plt.title("Monthly Prediction \n 1 year time frame")

plt.show()
